@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Course Notes";
}

<div class="container py-5">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
        <div class="col-12 text-center">
            <h1 class="display-3 fw-bold text-black mb-4">High Energy Astrophysics Course Notes</h1>
            <p class="fs-4 text-black">A collection of notes and resources for the course.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row justify-content-center my-5">
        <div class="col-12 text-center">
            <img src="~/images/Magnetar-FRB.jpg" alt="Magnetar-FRB" class="img-fluid rounded shadow-lg w-100" style="max-height: 500px; object-fit: cover;" />
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row justify-content-center">
        <div class="col-12">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
                    <div class="card shadow-lg p-4 bg-white text-black h-100">
                        <h2 class="card-title fw-bold">Chapter 1: Introduction to HEA</h2>
                        <p class="card-text text-secondary">
                            High-Energy Astrophysics (HEA) is a field of science that studies the most extreme physical phenomena in the universe. It focuses on the high-energy photons, such as X-rays and gamma-rays, emitted by massive objects like supernova explosions, black holes, and neutron stars. These photons can only be produced under conditions of extreme temperature and gravity, making them ideal tools for exploring the most intriguing and mysterious regions of the cosmos.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
                    <div class="card shadow-lg p-4 bg-white text-black h-100">
                        <h2 class="card-title fw-bold">Chapter 2: Research and Instruments</h2>
                        <p class="card-text text-secondary">
                            Research in this field provides deep insights into the fundamental structure and workings of the universe. For instance, high-energy observations help us understand the distribution of dark matter and the formation processes of galaxy clusters. This research also helps us understand the natural phenomena that act as cosmic particle accelerators, which can produce particles at energy levels that even the largest laboratories on Earth cannot reach.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row mt-4">
                <div class="col-12">
                    <div class="card shadow-lg p-4 bg-white text-black h-100">
                        <h2 class="card-title fw-bold">Chapter 3: Technological Applications and Future of HEA</h2>
                        <p class="card-text text-secondary">
                            High-Energy Astrophysics is not just a theoretical field. The X-ray telescopes and gamma-ray detectors used in this research have inspired practical applications, including medical imaging and security scanning technologies. Looking ahead, future missions will use advanced instrumentation to capture even fainter cosmic signals, allowing us to see further back in time and explore previously hidden aspects of the universe.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
